The Grade II* listed Hussey Tower was a 14- and 15th-century brick tower with an octagonal turret, originally known as Benyington Tower. It was sold to Boston Corporation and dismantled after 1545 when it was forfeited by [[Lord Hussey]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1388981|desc=Hussey Tower|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> 

Boston [[Workhouse]] was built in 1837 by George Gilbert Scott. It was built near the site of the [[medieval]] hospital of St John. The Grade II listed front range of the workhouse still exists, but the rear ranges were demolished in 1980.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1388982|desc=St Johns Buildings, Boston Workhouse|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> 

Boston [[House of correction]] was in Skirbeck Quarter and was erected in 1809. From 1826 it was only used to hold prisoners for trial, and after 1837 Boston borough gaol became available and Skirbeck House of correction closed. In 1849 it was converted into a [[Prison cell|lock-up]].<ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=1133287|mname= County House of Correction|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> 

[[Holy Trinity]] Grade II listed church in Skirbeck Quarter, which was a [[chapel of ease]] to Skirbeck, was built 1846<U+2013>48 by Sir George Gilbert Scott. In 1988 it was added to by John Webster of Leeds.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1389023|desc=Church of the Holy Trinity|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=1133287|mname= Skirbeck Quarter|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> 

[[Thomas the Apostle|Saint Thomas]] Church in Skirbeck Quarter started as a classroom of the original school building in 1866, and in 1885 became a "tin tabernacle". Need for a permanent brick building was recognised and the church was begun in 1909 and completed in 1912.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Thomas Church|url=http://www.parish-of-boston.org.uk/st-thomas.htm|work=Boston Parish|publisher=Parish of Boston|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> It was built by [[Temple Moore]] and is a Grade II listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1388920|desc=Church of St Thomas |accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> 

